##Question 1: What is the data showing? [5 marks] This is a data-set of 100 top tracks of 2018 From Spotify. Each row represents a track. The id column is the categorical variable which is the Spotifys identification of the song. The name column is also the categorical variable and shows the name of each video. The artists column is the categorical variable which displays artist(s) of the song. The danceability column is a numerical variable and displays how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. The energy column is the numerical variable which is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. The key column is the categorical variable. The key the track is in. Integers map to pitches using standard pitch Class notation. E.g. 0=C, 2=D, and so on. The loudness column is the numerical variable. The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). The mode column is the quantitative variable. Mode indicates the modality (major or minor) of a track, the type of scale from which its melodic content is derived. The speechiness column is the quantitative variable. Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g.talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. The acousticness column is the quantitative variable. A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. The instrumentalness column is the quantitative variable. Predicts whether a track contains no vocals. The liveness column is the quantitative variable which detects the presence of an audience in the recording. The valence column is the quantitative variable. Its a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. The tempo column is the quantitative variable. The overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM). The duration_ms column is the quantitative variable. It is the duration of the track in milliseconds. The time_signature column is the quantitative variable which is an estimated overall time signature of a track. The time signature (meter) is a notational convention to specify how many beats are in each bar (or measure).

Question 12: Explain the difference between the R2 value and the adjusted R2 value. You should described the difference in enough detail that I would be able to read out your words in class and for your classmates to understand what is going on. If you referred to online sources,references as needed. [5 marks]

One major difference between R-squared and the adjusted R-squared is that R-squared supposes that every independent variable in the model explains the variation in the dependent variable. Multiple R-squared is used for evaluating how well your model fits the data. They tell you how much of the variance in the dependent variable can be explained by the independent variables. Every time you add new variables, the R square value will increase irrespective of the variable significance. The higher the R squared, the more variation is explained by your input variables and hence better is your model. Adjusted R-squared also provides the same information as R-squared but adjusts for the number of terms in the model. It does not monotonically increase like R-squared but increases only when the new variable actually has an effect on the predicted value. It decreases when the new variable does not have any real impact on the predicted value.

Question 14: Conduct a hypothesis test to assess whether there a (linear) relationship between your explanatory and response variable. For example, as described in the latest lecture, use a t-test to determine if the slope, 1, of the population regression line = 0. Note, all the values you need for this are all included in summary(fit1). [14 marks]

H0:The loudness is not a significant explanotary variable for predicting energy (1=0) H1:The loudness is a significant explanotary variable for predicting energy (1 not equal to 0)

T=(0.05980-0)/0.00561 # use a t-test to determine if loudness is a significant explanotary variable for energy
2*pt(T,df=98,lower.tail = FALSE) # because it's two tails, so we should times two to get the p-value
## [1] 4.506288e-18

So p-value=4.506288e-18 which is smaller than 0.05, so we can reject hypothesis and conclude that we have sufficient evidence that the loudness is significant explanatory variable for predicting energy (1 not equal to 0)
